ce:section.ce:para:
To evaluate the impact of fin configuration and shell geometry on the thermal efficiency of LHS, an experimental apparatus (Fig. 2
                     ), described in our previous study [49], was employed to observe the development of the melting interface and to record temperature profiles at selected locations. In this study, six shell-and-tube LHS units were utilized. Two rectangular finned units [66] were adopted from our previous research, while four additional units were fabricated, featuring two distinct internal fin configurations: Y-shaped and tree-shaped. Each fin type was incorporated into both obround and circular shell designs, enabling a comprehensive investigation of the combined influence of shell geometry and fin configuration. Detailed views of the fabricated HXs, illustrating the fin types and shell designs, are presented in Fig. 3
                     .
